VALUES
(43, 6, 38, 40, 26, 39, 42, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize submission to God''s will. In John, Jesus states he came to do the will of the Father, while in Matthew, he expresses a desire for God''s will over his own. This connection highlights the theme of obedience to divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 58, 10, 7, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize the commitment to do ''thy will, O God.'' This connection highlights the obedience of Jesus to God''s will, contrasting with the previous sacrificial system.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 43, 17, 12, 12, NULL, 'Preservation of the Given', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of keeping those given by the Father. John 6:39 states that nothing given to Jesus will be lost, while John 17:12 reiterates that none were lost except for the son of perdition.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 43, 6, 40, 40, 'raise it up again at the last day', 'Connection of God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the will of the Father regarding those given to the Son. They highlight the promise of raising believers up at the last day, linking the assurance of eternal life with divine intention.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 45, 8, 11, 11, 'raise it up again at the last day', 'Resurrection and Eternal Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in both passages. John 6:39 speaks of raising up at the last day, while Romans 8:11 emphasizes being quickened by the Spirit, linking the promise of resurrection to believers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 65, 1, 1, 1, 'should lose nothing', 'Preservation and Calling', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of preservation in relation to believers. John 6:39 speaks of losing nothing of what the Father has given, while Jude 1:1 mentions being preserved in Jesus Christ, highlighting God''s commitment to safeguard His followers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 50, 3, 20, 21, 'raise it up again at the last day', 'Resurrection and Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in both passages. John 6:39 speaks of raising up believers at the last day, while Philippians 3:21 discusses the transformation of our bodies to be like Christ''s glorious body.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 53, 2, 13, 14, 'lose nothing', 'Divine Election and Preservation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine selection and preservation of believers. John 6:39 emphasizes that none given to Jesus will be lost, while 2 Thessalonians 2:13-14 speaks of God choosing individuals for salvation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 39, 40, 18, 14, 14, 'the Fatherâ€™s will', 'Divine Will for Preservation', 'Both passages emphasize the Father''s will to ensure that none of His given ones perish. John 6:39 states that He will lose nothing, while Matthew 18:14 highlights that it is not His will for any little ones to perish.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 43, 5, 24, 24, 'everlasting life', 'Connection of Everlasting Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of everlasting life for those who believe. They highlight the importance of faith in the Son and the one who sent him as the means to attain this life.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 43, 6, 54, 54, 'I will raise him up at the last day', 'Eternal Life and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of eternal life and the assurance of being raised up at the last day. They connect through the theme of belief in Jesus as essential for receiving everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 45, 6, 23, 23, 'everlasting life', 'Eternal Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of eternal life. John 6:40 speaks of everlasting life for those who believe in the Son, while Romans 6:23 contrasts death with the gift of eternal life through Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 42, 2, 30, 30, 'believeth on him, may have everlasting life', 'Connection of Salvation and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of salvation. John 6:40 speaks of believing in the Son for everlasting life, while Luke 2:30 expresses seeing salvation. This connection highlights the importance of recognizing and believing in God''s provision for salvation.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 62, 1, 1, 3, 'everlasting life', 'Eternal Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of eternal life. John 6:40 speaks of those who believe in the Son having everlasting life, while 1 John 1:2 refers to the manifestation of eternal life. This connection highlights the continuity of the message about eternal life through belief in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 62, 2, 25, 25, 'everlasting life', 'Eternal Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of eternal life. John 6:40 speaks of the promise of everlasting life for believers, while 1 John 2:25 directly states that God has promised us eternal life.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 40, 23, 45, 21, 22, NULL, 'Salvation and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of salvation through belief. John 6:40 speaks of everlasting life for those who believe in the Son, while Isaiah 45:22 calls all to look to God for salvation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 43, 6, 51, 52, 'I am the bread which came down from heaven', 'Connection of Bread from Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''bread which came down from heaven.'' The Jews'' reaction in both instances highlights their struggle to understand Jesus'' teaching about the significance of this bread, leading to confusion over eating his flesh.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 43, 6, 33, 33, 'I am the bread which came down from heaven', 'Connection of Bread from Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''bread which came down from heaven.'' This connection highlights the significance of Jesus as the source of life for the world.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 42, 5, 30, 30, 'murmured', 'Murmuring Against Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of murmuring against Jesus and his actions. Both passages depict a negative response from religious leaders towards Jesus and his disciples, indicating a shared tension in their ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 42, 15, 2, 2, 'murmured', 'Murmuring in Response to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of murmuring in response to Jesus'' actions and statements. In both passages, the Jews and the Pharisees express discontent, reflecting a common reaction to Jesus'' teachings and associations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 65, 1, 16, 16, 'murmured at him', 'Murmuring and Complaining', 'This connection highlights the theme of murmuring in both passages. In John 6:41, the Jews murmur against Jesus, while Jude 1:16 describes individuals as murmurers and complainers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 41, 46, 10, 10, 10, 'murmured', 'Murmuring and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the act of murmuring against God. In John, the Jews murmur about Jesus as the bread from heaven, while in Corinthians, the warning against murmuring recalls the consequences faced by those who did so in the past.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 42, 4, 22, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as Joseph''s son, highlighting the familiarity of his earthly origins. This connection raises questions about his divine claims, as seen in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 40, 13, 55, 56, 'Is not this Jesus, the son of Joseph', 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the familiarity of Jesus'' earthly origins, questioning how he can claim divine authority. They highlight the disbelief of those who know his family background, suggesting a theme of skepticism regarding his heavenly claims.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 41, 6, 3, 3, 'Is not this Jesus, the son of Joseph', 'Jesus'' Identity and Origins', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' earthly origins and familial connections. In John 6:42, the crowd questions how Jesus can claim to have come down from heaven, given their familiarity with his parents. Similarly, Mark 6:3 refers to Jesus as the son of Mary and mentions his brothers and sisters, highlighting the same theme of his human background.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 43, 7, 27, 28, 'I came down from heaven', 'Identity of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' origins. In John 6:42, the crowd questions how Jesus can claim to have come down from heaven, while in John 7:27-28, Jesus asserts that they know him and his origins, yet he is sent by the true God, whom they do not know.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 46, 15, 47, 47, 'I came down from heaven', 'Heavenly Origin of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus'' earthly origins and His divine nature. John 6:42 questions how Jesus, known as the son of Joseph, claims to have come down from heaven, while 1 Corinthians 15:47 identifies Him as the Lord from heaven.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 43, 6, 38, 38, 'I came down from heaven', 'Connection of Divine Origin', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' claim of divine origin, with John 6:42 questioning how he can say he ''came down from heaven,'' while John 6:38 asserts that he indeed came down to fulfill God''s will. This connection highlights the tension between Jesus'' earthly identity and his heavenly mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 42, 45, 1, 3, 4, 'I came down from heaven', 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the dual nature of Jesus as both human and divine. John 6:42 questions Jesus'' heavenly origin, while Romans 1:3-4 affirms His divine sonship and resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 43, 58, 4, 13, 13, 'murmur not among yourselves', 'Awareness of Divine Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of awareness of one''s thoughts and actions before God. Both passages emphasize the idea that nothing is hidden from God''s sight, encouraging believers to be mindful of their inner dialogue and attitudes.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
